    <h2>Geelong — Heritage Homes, Cold Winters and Chimneys That Work Hard</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Geelong is Victoria's second-largest city and has one of the most significant stocks of heritage housing outside Melbourne. The inner suburbs — Newtown, Geelong West, South Geelong, Drumcondra and the CBD fringe — are full of original Victorian and Edwardian period homes with solid brick chimneys and open fireplaces built as primary heat sources well over a century ago. Many of these systems are still in daily use. The original lime mortar, brick flue liners and narrow Victorian flue dimensions accumulate creosote and soot faster than modern systems, and require experienced handling. Beyond the heritage core, Geelong's middle and outer suburbs — Belmont, Highton, Grovedale, Corio, Lara and surrounds — contain a large stock of 1960s through 1990s homes with freestanding wood heaters. Geelong's winters are cold and often windswept, with consistent overnight lows that mean wood heating runs hard from May through August. Regular chimney and flue cleaning keeps these systems safe and efficient through the season.</p></div>
  </section>

